"Abstract The recent Democratic and Republican National Conventions rolled out their respective party platforms on a number of policy issues, including cyber-security and data privacy. A close examination of the platforms reveals very little difference between the two parties on information policy issues. Although presidential candidates seldom abide by the policies enunciated on the platforms, the gist of the party planks indicate that both the Democrats and Republicans generally favour industry self-regulation of privacy issues and an increased government role in cyber-defence and information warfare."
